<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000033.tif" N="[1]">
<HEAD>[IACOB AND IOSEP]<NOTE PLACE="foot">No heading in MS.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Wolle &yogh;e nou ihere wordes swi&thorn;e gode<MILESTONE N="1a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of one patriarke after Noees flode?</L>
<L>Nellic &yogh;ou nou&yogh;t tellen of &thorn;is flodes grame,</L>
<L>Bote of one patriarke, Iacob was his name.</L>
<L N="5">While men loueden meri song, gamen &amp; feire tale;</L>
<L>Nou hem is wel leuere gon to &thorn;e nale,</L>
<L>Vcchen out &thorn;e gurdel &amp; rume &thorn;e wombe,</L>
<L>Comen erliche &thorn;ider &amp; sitte &thorn;er ful longe.</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e soule ful lo&thorn;, &amp; lef &thorn;e licame,</L>
<L N="10">Bote we hit bileuen, hit bi&thorn; a lu&thorn;er game.</L>
<L>To fullen oure wombe hit is lutel pris,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e ligge slepe, such hit were a gris.</L>
<L>&THORN;us ferden oure aldren bi Noees dawe,</L>
<L>Of mete &amp; of drinke hi fulden here mawe;</L>
<L N="15">&amp; for &yogh;iuernesse &thorn;ei weren ri&yogh;t wod;</L>
<L>For &thorn;i sende oure Louerd Noees flod.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hi mi&yogh;ten drinke &thorn;at hi weren fulle,</L>
<L>Hi floten swi&thorn;e riued bi dich &amp; bi pulle.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas in &thorn;is world hul non so hei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at tis vnirude flod muchel ne ouerstei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Nou ich wole fon on &thorn;er ich er let,</L>
<L>&amp; tellen ou of Iacob, so ich &yogh;ou bihet.</L>
<L>Iacob liuede in londe &amp; louede Godes lawe</L>
<L>So dude Ysaac his fader bi his lifdawe.</L>
<L N="25">Iacob liuede in londe, &amp; feire he ladde his lif,</L>
<L>Sones he wan ten on Lya his wif;
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="2"></L>
<L>On Rachel he wan tweye, Iosep &amp; Beniamin.</L>
<L>Betere is for to here &thorn;is tale &thorn;en to drinke win;<MILESTONE N="1b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For whoso here&thorn; &thorn;is tale to &thorn;e nendinge,</L>
<L N="30">Of more reufule song herde he neuere singe.</L>
<L>Nou he sit in halle, Iacob &thorn;e elde man,</L>
<L>&amp; his sones alle from felde come&thorn; hom.</L>
<L>Iacob bihalt his sones, of hem he was bli&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&amp; Iosep &thorn;e &yogh;unge bigan to speke swi&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="35">His fader he tolde a swefne ani&yogh;t &thorn;at him mette</L>
<L>&amp; bad swi&thorn;e &yogh;erne telle &thorn;at me him lette.</L>
<L>'Do nou, mi sone dere, God leue &thorn;e so to speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tou in none worde his heste ne tobreke.'</L>
<L>'Vader,' seide Iosep, 'nou ich wole &thorn;e telle</L>
<L N="40">Of mine metinge &amp; of mine spelle.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;u&yogh;te, ase ich slepte, afeld &thorn;at we were,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &amp; mi moder &amp; mine bre&thorn;ren here;</L>
<L>&amp; so we repen oure corn &amp; oure sseues knetten,</L>
<L>&amp; vpri&yogh;t in &thorn;e felde wel feire we hem setten,</L>
<L N="45">Me &thorn;u&yogh;te &thorn;at &yogh;oure sseues, &thorn;er hi stoden alle,</L>
<L>To me &thorn;ei gonnen louten &amp; to mi fet falle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it me &thorn;u&yogh;te an o&thorn;er, fader, God hit wot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at te sunne &amp; &thorn;e mone fellen to mi fot.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it me &thorn;u&yogh;te &thorn;e &thorn;ridde, fader, telli &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;at elleue sterren to fote fellen me.</L>
<L>&THORN;is is mi sweuene, fader, &thorn;at ich telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hit &thorn;i wille were, ared what hit mai be.'</L>
<L>&THORN;enne seide Iacob to Iosep his sone,</L>
<L>'Tide wat bitide, &yogh;it wole &thorn;i swefne come.</L>
<L N="55">Tide wat bitide, &yogh;it wole &thorn;i swefne be.<MILESTONE N="2a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ich wene mid iwisse, &yogh;ut we hit ssulen ise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich &amp; &thorn;i moder &amp; &thorn;ine bre&thorn;ren ek</L>
<L>Moten for fine nede comen to &thorn;ine fet.'
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="3"></L>
<L>&THORN;is iherden his bre&thorn;ren, &thorn;erfore hem was ful wo,</L>
<L N="60">Hi gonnen hatie Iosep ase here fulle fo.</L>
<L>&THORN;au alle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alle</I>] MS. <I>alla&dotb;e.</I></NOTE> his ten bre&thorn;ren &thorn;erfore hateden hine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure Louerd wole habben ido mai no man binime</L>
<L>&THORN;is bre&thorn;ren wende&thorn; afeld to witen here fe,</L>
<L>Ac Iosep leuede at hom, &thorn;at hende was &amp; fre.</L>
<L N="65">Iacob sit in halle &amp; clepe&thorn; Iosep his sone;</L>
<L>&THORN;at child swi&thorn;e sone to his fader is icome.</L>
<L>At his fader fot &thorn;at child him sit akne,</L>
<L>&amp; axe&thorn; him wel feire wat his wille be.</L>
<L>Sone seide Iacob, 'Wende &thorn;ou most afeld</L>
<L N="70">To seche &thorn;ine bre&thorn;ren, &amp; wer be here teld.</L>
<L>Bring vs hom tiding hu &thorn;ine bre&thorn;ren fare.</L>
<L>Vre Louerd, &thorn;at is in heuene, berewe &thorn;e from care.'</L>
<L>Iosep ge&thorn; afeldward, euel ne &thorn;ou&yogh;te he non,</L>
<L>He wende to sechen his bre&thorn;ren, &amp; sou&yogh;te his fulle fon.</L>
<L>He seche&thorn; hem, ne mai he hem finde, &thorn;erfore him was wo;</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;enne fond a man al one &thorn;e child wondrinde go.</L>
<L>&THORN;is man axede &thorn;at child woder he wolde te;</L>
<L>Iosep his bre&thorn;ren seche&thorn; &amp; fain hem wolde ise.</L>
<L>&THORN;e man onswerede &thorn;at child, &amp; &thorn;us he spac to him,</L>
<L N="80">'Hi be&thorn; in one felde, hatte Dotaym;</L>
<L>Ac lutel er hi weren in Sichem, bi hem ich stod &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Child, &yogh;if &thorn;ou hem wolt finde, to Dotaym &thorn;u go.<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Child, &yogh;if &thorn;ou hem wolt finde, to Dotaym &thorn;u go ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Also ich vnderstonde, &thorn;er &thorn;u hem finde mi&yogh;t.'</L>
<L N="85">Iosep mid gode wille &thorn;iderward he ge&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;er alle hise ten bre&thorn;ren habbe&thorn; isworen his de&thorn;.</L>
<L>He cam toward his bre&thorn;ren, &thorn;at ternde ssolde bere,</L>
<L>Hi sigge&thorn; hem bitwene, 'Her come&thorn; &thorn;e metere.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>Nime we &amp; quellen &thorn;is ilke hinderling,</L>
<L N="90">&amp; loke&thorn; wat him ssal helpe &thorn;erafter his meting.'</L>
<L>He cam to his bre&thorn;ren &amp; grettem eueruchon;</L>
<L>Hi &thorn;enche&thorn; al an o&thorn;er, &amp; gripe&thorn; him anon.</L>
<L>Quellen him hi wolle&thorn;, nou hi him habbe&thorn; inome,</L>
<L>Ac Ruben, &thorn;at o bro&thorn;er, he spac atte frome,</L>
<L N="95">'A dep pet is her bisides &thorn;at water er &thorn;is in stod;</L>
<L>Worpe&thorn; &thorn;erinne Iosep, ssende we nou&yogh;t oure blod,'</L>
<L>(Iosep for to helpe Ruben spac &thorn;is tale)</L>
<L>'&YOGH;if we &thorn;is child aquelle&thorn;, hit be&thorn; oure fader bale.'</L>
<L>His fader him &yogh;af a kurtel &thorn;at rum was &amp; wid,</L>
<L N="100">Wel hit bicam &thorn;e child, hit was him fotsid.</L>
<L>Hi strupten of &thorn;e curtel, of swere &amp; of chin,</L>
<L>Al naked in &thorn;e pette hi worpen &thorn;at child in.</L>
<L>Ac Ruben, &thorn;at o bro&thorn;er, &thorn;enne he is igo,</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;te he for reu&thorn;e atte pette be &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;is o&thorn;re sitte&thorn; bisides &amp; fo&thorn; on here mete,</L>
<L>&THORN;enche&thorn; hi nei&thorn;er of serewe ne of hete.</L>
<L>Iosep sit in pette mid ful sori mod,</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;ren law&yogh;e&thorn; loude, &thorn;at gamen hem &thorn;inke&thorn; god.</L>
<L>Nou Iosep sit in pette &amp; wringe&thorn; his honde.<MILESTONE N="3a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="110">A wey, &thorn;at bitwene bre&thorn;ren ssal be &thorn;us muchel onde!</L>
<L>Nou drawen him vp hi wolle&thorn;, &amp; quellen him atte frome,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne seien hi bisides twei riche chapmen come.</L>
<L>Vrom a lond hi comen, Galaad ihoten is,</L>
<L>Mid here assen isemed of fer &amp; of gris.</L>
<L N="115">Of stor &amp; of spices &thorn;ei ladden grete male</L>
<L>Into Egipte lond to sullen hit to sale.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne spac him Iuda, he spac atte frome,</L>
<L>'Wolle we sullen Iosep &thorn;is chapmen &thorn;at here come?</L>
<L>Fer into Egypte lond hi him wolle&thorn; lede,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;enne wor&thorn; his sweuen e&thorn; to arede.'
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>Hi comen to &thorn;is chapmen &amp; sseweden here tale,</L>
<L>Iosep in &thorn;e pette hi chepeden to sale.</L>
<L>&THORN;is chapmen be&thorn; wise &amp; axe&thorn; wer he be.</L>
<L>'Come&thorn; ner,' hi seiden, '&amp; &yogh;e him mowen ise;</L>
<L N="125">Hit is a swi&thorn;e feir child &amp; of kunne hei&yogh;.'</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;at ilke worde &thorn;e pet hi weren nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Hi drowen vp Iosep mid one longe rope,</L>
<L>Ac one gode while ne mi&yogh;te he speke for wope.</L>
<L>&THORN;is chapmen biholde&thorn; Iosep, &thorn;at be&thorn; swi&thorn;e wis,</L>
<L N="130">&amp; Iosep to begge swi&thorn;e lef hem is.</L>
<L>Hi chepe&thorn; &amp; hi bede&thorn;, sone hi be&thorn; at on.</L>
<L>Iosep wrang his honden &amp; was ful sori man.</L>
<L>Hi casten hond to purse, &thorn;e panes be&thorn; itold;</L>
<L>Nou helpe Crist Iosep, so &yogh;ung he is isold.</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;is chapmen fenge&thorn; &thorn;at child, &thorn;is bre&thorn;ren &thorn;at fe;</L>
<L>Darf no man axe wer Iosep sori be;<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For euere ase hi hine lede&thorn;, euer he wepe&thorn;,</L>
<L>His fader &amp; his moder &yogh;ung he forlete&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;is chapmen be&thorn; wel bli&thorn;e &thorn;at Iosep habbe&thorn; ibou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="140">&amp; vpon &thorn;e sestronde hi him habbe&thorn; ibrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;is chapmen nime&thorn; Iosep ri&yogh;t bi &thorn;e hond,</L>
<L>&amp; so hi lede&thorn; Iosep into Egipte lond.</L>
<L>Ac of Egiptene speche cou&thorn;e he no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>For &thorn;i he wepte sore, &thorn;is ilke &yogh;ungling.</L>
<L N="145">Hi ladden Iosep into &thorn;e bur&yogh;, &thorn;at riche was &amp; strong:</L>
<L>Castles heie &amp; proute, stretes wide &amp; long,</L>
<L>Mani feir halle &amp; mani feir bour,</L>
<L>Whit so eni lilie, bri&yogh;t so eni flour.</L>
<L>Muche was &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at was in &thorn;e bur&yogh;,</L>
<L N="150">Iosep for to sullen hi ladden &thorn;ur&yogh; &amp; &thorn;ur&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;ider comen kni&yogh;tes &amp; burgeis ful bolde,</L>
<L>Hi comen into &thorn;e strete Iosep to biholde.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>Leuedis of boure &amp; maidenes fre</L>
<L>Comen into &thorn;e strete Iosep to ise.</L>
<L N="155">Ac &thorn;er &thorn;u&yogh;te muche wonder mani a moder sone,</L>
<L>Hem &thorn;u&yogh;te hit was an angel from heuene icome.</L>
<L>Ful sone &thorn;e tiding of Iosep hit sprong</L>
<L>To Putifar &thorn;e stiward of Egipte lond.</L>
<L>Putifar &thorn;e stiward &thorn;ider he is icome,</L>
<L N="160">&amp; in his ferade mani a kni&yogh;tes sone.</L>
<L>So sone so &thorn;e stiward on Iosep bihuld,</L>
<L>He li&yogh;te of his stede, his mantel he vnfuld,</L>
<L>Cofre he lette vnlouke &amp; gold casten out anon,<MILESTONE N="4a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sone he bou&yogh;te Iosep of &thorn;is chapmon.</L>
<L N="165">More &thorn;en he axede for Iosep he &yogh;af,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en on his stede wel feire he him haf.</L>
<L>Nou lete we Iosep ride, God ssilde him from care,</L>
<L>&amp; vte we speken of Iacob his fader, hou he fare.</L>
<L>Nou he sit in halle, Iacob &thorn;e elde man,</L>
<L N="170">&amp; his sones ten from<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS.<I>fron.</I></NOTE> felde come&thorn; hom,</L>
<L>&amp; Ioseppes curtel hi bringe&thorn; al blodi,</L>
<L>&THORN;o Iacob hit gan biholde iwis he was sori.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he sau&yogh; his kurtel ispreind al wi&thorn; blod,</L>
<L>Nas neuere for his child fader so sorimod.</L>
<L N="175">Adoun he fel iswowe &amp; tar his hore loc,</L>
<L>&THORN;e moder feng to renden hire neb &amp; hire smoc.</L>
<L>Euer seide &thorn;e moder, 'Wo is me a liue,</L>
<L>For mi sone Iosep be ich neuere bli&thorn;e.'</L>
<L>Euere seide Iacob, 'Iosep is islawe,</L>
<L N="180">O&thorn;er summe lu&thorn;ere deres habbe&thorn; him todrawe.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ider comen manie of fremede &amp; o kinne</L>
<L>For to gladen Iacob, ac his sones hadden sinne.</L>
<L>Woso seye Iacob his sorinesse lede,
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>Hit were muche reu&thorn;e in boc for to rede.</L>
<L N="185">Nou Iacob sit in halle &amp; wringe&thorn; his honde,</L>
<L>We ssule speken of Iosep in Egipte londe.</L>
<L>Nou Putifar ssrude&thorn; Iosep mid derewor&thorn;e ssroud,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;iue&thorn; him Pharaon &thorn;e king, mid him he is proud.</L>
<L>Nou is Iosep feir child in Pharaones halle,</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;e pore &amp; &thorn;e riche louie&thorn; him alle.<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tofore &thorn;e king selue he serue&thorn; atte bord,</L>
<L>Of pore &amp; of riche he ha&thorn; wel god word.</L>
<L>Hit fel in one daye, &thorn;e king was out iwent</L>
<L>To &thorn;e wode to ssete mid his bowe ibent.</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;e quene louede Iosep ase hir owe lif,</L>
<L>Heo sente him after sone to speken hire wi&thorn;.</L>
<L>Ac of &thorn;isse &thorn;inge nuste Iosep ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Aru&yogh; hit were to knowe alle wimmanes &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;er wimman is god, nis non so swete &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="200">For al &thorn;at euere Eue brac in paradis</L>
<L>Oure leuedi hit bette, &thorn;at derewor&thorn;est is.</L>
<L>Iosep cam to boure, &thorn;at hende was &amp; fre.</L>
<L>'Leuedi,' quod Iosep, 'wat &thorn;i wille be?'</L>
<L>'Iosep,' quod &thorn;e quene, 'nou &thorn;ou art welcome,</L>
<L N="205">Nou in mine boure ich &thorn;e haue inome.</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e wole tellen one tidinge,</L>
<L>Ich wole &thorn;e make richest man after oure kinge.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ssalt habbe &thorn;i wil of fer &amp; of gris,</L>
<L>Of gold &amp; of seluer, of al &thorn;at feir is.</L>
<L N="210">&THORN;ou ssalt haue &thorn;i wil of al Egipte londe,</L>
<L>Ssal neuere no man &thorn;ine heste astonde.</L>
<L>&amp; of one &thorn;inge iwis &thorn;u mi&yogh;t be bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no man me so lef &thorn;at euere is aliue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou canst in boure louie me derne,</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;e prute of Egipte ssal &thorn;e nou&yogh;t be werne.'
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>Mid &thorn;at ilke worde heo gan him cluppe &amp; kisse.</L>
<L>'Iosep, ich am &thorn;in,' heo seide, 'mid iwisse.'<MILESTONE N="5a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Iosep of &thorn;ese wordes nas he no &thorn;ing glad,</L>
<L>He nolde in none wise don ase &thorn;e quene him bad.</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;ei&yogh; Iosep were in boure stille bisteke,</L>
<L>He nolde in none wise his trou&thorn;e tobreke.</L>
<L>Mid his white fingres hire armes he vnfeld,</L>
<L>&amp; wende from &thorn;e quene, ac his mantel heo athuld.</L>
<L>Heo braid of hire wimpel &amp; loude feng to reme,</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;er come serians wel fele for to nime &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>Wat here leuedi mi&yogh;te be, &thorn;at hem was so lef.</L>
<L>'A! Loke&thorn; nou,' heo seide, '&thorn;is Ebrewisse &thorn;ef,</L>
<L>Of me he wende stille to habben his gome,</L>
<L>Nas neuere quene in &thorn;is lond ido so muche ssome.'</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;e king cam from &thorn;e wode mid blowinde beme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quene fel to his fet &amp; loude feng to reme,</L>
<L>&amp; tolde &thorn;e king of &thorn;is muchele ssome,</L>
<L>&THORN;unche hit no wonder &thorn;ei&yogh; he ne hadde grome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him lette nime &amp; ful faste binde:</L>
<L N="235">Nou ne mai Iosep nenne frend finde.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;is iherde &thorn;erfore weren ful wo:</L>
<L>Summe for &thorn;e quene, ac for Iosep wel mo.</L>
<L>Nou is Iosep so wo &thorn;at he not wat he mai:</L>
<L>Bide neuere no god man non so sori dai.</L>
<L N="240">Ac heuede Iosep ido ase &thorn;e quene him bad,</L>
<L>He mi&yogh;te ben in halle mid o&thorn;re bli&thorn;e &amp; glad.</L>
<L>Gulteles in &thorn;e pette his bre&thorn;ren hine dude,</L>
<L>&amp; gulteles he is nou&thorn;e in ful &thorn;estri stede.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;er he is ful longe muche wo to abide,<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="245">Oure Louerd he hit &thorn;onke&thorn;, tide wat bitide.</L>
<L>Hit fel in one daye to &thorn;e newe &yogh;er,</L>
<L>Iwreyed was wel stronge &thorn;e kinges botiler,</L>
<P>
